==English==

===Etymology===
Derived from Middle French '''sacquer''' (meaning "to push") + '''bouter''' (meaning "to pull")

===Noun===
{{Wikipedia}}
'''sackbut'''

====Variant Spellings====
'''sacbut'''<br />'''sagbut'''<br />'''shagbolt'''<br />'''shakbusshe'''

#''Music''. A [[brass instrument]] from the Renaissance and Baroque Eras, and is an ancestor of the modern [[trombone]]. It was derived from the medieval slide [[trumpet]].

